    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_830773695" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/830773695" />
    <a title="Adam Dalva" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3263980-adam-dalva"><img alt="Adam Dalva" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1629300413p2/3263980.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/830773695?book_show_action=true">Jan 21, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adam Dalva" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adam Dalva" href="/user/show/3263980-adam-dalva">Adam Dalva</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3263980-adam-dalva?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer830773695" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6583075107566656720">A winter book - one of the strangest experiences I&apos;ve had reading. It is a slow go without ever being remarkably difficult. I could never (except for the ending, which does ramp up) manage more than 50 pages in a day. And yet, as I became familiar with Mann&apos;s cadence and goals, there was a dizzy pleasure to it. This is the second piece of writing ever that has made me miss a subway stop - the first was &quot;A Supposedly Fun Thing&quot; - and, bizarrely enough, the precipitating moment was Hans Castorp as</span>
  <span id="freeText6583075107566656720" style="display:none">A winter book - one of the strangest experiences I've had reading. It is a slow go without ever being remarkably difficult. I could never (except for the ending, which does ramp up) manage more than 50 pages in a day. And yet, as I became familiar with Mann's cadence and goals, there was a dizzy pleasure to it. This is the second piece of writing ever that has made me miss a subway stop - the first was "A Supposedly Fun Thing" - and, bizarrely enough, the precipitating moment was Hans Castorp asking Claudia if he could borrow her pencil. That was the entire, exhilarating scene, made special by context, by familiarity with the characters (in this instance, acting out of character), by the way everything in this book becomes super-charged.<br /><br />The lesson is one of Relativism, which reminds me so much of Pnin's charming speech about Anna Karenina. Literature always works on a sort of odd exponential decay w/r/t time, but I have never read something that was so conscious about it. Roughly, the first week takes as long as the first month takes as long as the first year takes as long as five years, and the narration giddily points it out all the time. We feel all this time pass (it's somewhat related to the experience of time seeming to go faster as we age), and so the simplest acts, like pencil-borrowing or switching tables at breakfast, are magnified. The time frame allows Mann to modulate the setting and cast - it seems like something that could have gone on forever. The ending is brilliant, despite being an easy out.<br /><br />This relativism applies to characters too, most noticeably to Settembrini, the most annoying good character I've encountered so far, a joyful monologuer, an Italian secular humanist. Mann eventually somehow conjures an even more loathsome counterpoint, a Hegelian (I think) Jesuit, and they debate. Oh do they debate. 15 pages in a stretch at one point, with two extreme sides of an argument, and whereas before Settembrini seemed like a blowhard, he becomes delightful and empathetic merely by the contrast. Now, these scenes, I sometimes wanted to hate, to skip, but I read all of them under the spell of the book. More delightful is Hans himself, who gains mastery of speech, of self, of perspective over the course of the narrative. It's the classic bildungsroman idea taken to an extreme - we grow up with him, and we tolerate his "ordinaryness," love it even, and enjoy his flaws. <br /><br />Oh, it's really romantic too. Like, achingly so.<br /><br />Two points<br />1: It might not sound like it, but the book is hilarious, both for character beats and for meta humor. <br />2: I think you could posit an argument that despite the early publication date this is one of those missing links between the Modernists and the Post-Modernists. It's in the former school, but the intentional boredom and the narrator felt really beyond the time to me.<br /><br />For all this talk, it's a book of moments: Hans's great skiing misadventure, his flashback to his youthful gay crush, Claudia banging the door open, Joachim (an all-timer of a character) saying "Hans" only once, Settembrini's nicknames, the Director's painting of Claudia, the night of carnival, the waterfall, snowflakes, flowers, dancing. The way the book functions, the time it takes, invests these scenes with joy. There are missteps, huge ones (oh boy could I have done without the ghost stuff), and the thing requires a ton of patience, but it is worth it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6583075107566656720" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

