  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_606548129" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/606548129" />
    <a title="Mike" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7272380-mike"><img alt="Mike" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1548615999p2/7272380.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/606548129?book_show_action=true">Dec 01, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mike" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mike" href="/user/show/7272380-mike">Mike</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7272380-mike?shelf=in-the-mountains">in-the-mountains</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7272380-mike?shelf=over-600-pages">over-600-pages</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7272380-mike?shelf=2021">2021</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7272380-mike?shelf=germany">germany</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7272380-mike?shelf=read-during-global-pandemic">read-during-global-pandemic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7272380-mike?shelf=stranger-in-a-strange-land">stranger-in-a-strange-land</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7272380-mike?shelf=failed-visionary-cults">failed-visionary-cults</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7272380-mike?shelf=the-20s">the-20s</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7272380-mike?shelf=eros-and-thanatos">eros-and-thanatos</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer606548129" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14816418847614185942"><br/>I know I&apos;m not the only person who&apos;s had <i>The Magic Mountain</i> (1924) on the shelf (figuratively speaking, in my case*) for a few years, occasionally glancing over at it and wondering what the experience of reading it is like, whether it&apos;s worthwhile, what its deal is. So now that I&apos;ve read it, I feel some degree of responsibility to send back word from the summit. It probably couldn&apos;t hurt at the outset then to mention two thematically-relevant songs that kept playing in my head throughout the cli</span>
  <span id="freeText14816418847614185942" style="display:none"><br />I know I'm not the only person who's had <i>The Magic Mountain</i> (1924) on the shelf (figuratively speaking, in my case*) for a few years, occasionally glancing over at it and wondering what the experience of reading it is like, whether it's worthwhile, what its deal is. So now that I've read it, I feel some degree of responsibility to send back word from the summit. It probably couldn't hurt at the outset then to mention two thematically-relevant songs that kept playing in my head throughout the climb. The first is "Should I Stay or Should I Go" by The Clash, and the second is "Heaven" by Talking Heads, the chorus of which goes: "Heaven is a place...where nothing ever happens." <br /><br /><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaZZcRB01kQ" rel="nofollow noopener">This lecture</a> (not recommended until after you've read the book) also helped me to contextualize the novel in Mann's life and career, as well as to some small extent in German culture and history. According to the professor, this idea of going to the mountains and becoming enchanted- an enchantment that is both erotic and closely linked to death- goes way back in German history. Maybe so, but if we merely substitute wilderness and nature in general for mountains specifically, I'd say I have noticed that theme just about everywhere in popular culture (give or take the eroticism), from <i>Picnic at Hanging Rock</i> to <i>Grizzly Man</i> to <i>Into Thin Air</i> and <i>Into the Wild</i>, not to mention that it's the theme of pretty much <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2748956536?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1" rel="nofollow noopener">every Algernon Blackwood story</a>. Like Blackwood's protagonists, Mann's Hans Castorp is inexorably drawn towards some strange, vaguely erotic oblivion- or as some of us call it, Friday evening. <br /><br />In any case, <i>The Magic Mountain</i> begins with young engineer Hans Castorp arriving at the Berghof tuberculosis sanatorium in the Swiss Alps to spend a few weeks with his sick cousin Joachim. For a while there in the beginning, I picked up on a bit of a thriller vibe- the kind of story in which a new arrival to a hermetic, seemingly idyllic community slowly discovers its dark secrets. And I guess that <i>is</i> one way to describe the novel, except that anyone who truly expects a thriller is going to have to adjust expectations pretty dramatically. Still, there's an eeriness to these early chapters, as it's hinted that Hans, though ostensibly a visitor, is well-suited- maybe a little <i>too</i> well-suited- to the timeless inertia of the mountain, where the residents spend hours every day in "rest cure", which simply involves lying horizontally on their balconies, and not moving. In other words, rest cure is...nothing. Although the patients don't do a bad imitation of the dead. It's a neat idea, Hans slowly and ominously becoming more amenable to the world of the sanatorium, though Mann lessens the effect just a little by overplaying his hand. I could swear that throughout the first 100 pages or so, for example, on nearly every other page, Mann has Hans think something along the lines of, "...but then again, of course, there's nothing wrong with falling into the everyday routine of the residents here...after all, I'm not sick like them, I'm <i>well</i>, and I'll be departing next week." We get it, Tom- Hans is going to be on the mountain for a long time.<br /><br />Mann is not exactly a subtle foreshadower, an aspect of the novel that it took me a while to get used to. On a line-by-line level, the writing is not bad at all, but I can't say Mann's style is right up my alley, either. The blurb on the book cover actually puts it well- the prose is "ironically elegant"- and, I would add, mellifluous, often seizing on the lofty idea, on the abstract and the aesthetic, reflecting seemingly little interest in the physical realities of life. The same is true of the dialogue. They say that this is a novel of ideas. But for a novel that's also about sickness, it's not very corporeal- it's hard to imagine Settembrini just scratching his ass, or Naphta picking his nose. Even in the chapter "Snow", which seems to be popular, I've got to say that I never felt that Hans was lost in a snowstorm. I felt like Mann's <i>idea</i> about a character being lost in a snowstorm had triggered a series of further ideas and associations about what that situation might be like, what thoughts a character might have, etc.- Mann isn't very interested in verisimilitude. And even when a character does something physical that sticks in the memory- Clavdia slamming the door in the dining hall, for example- that physical action is often mentioned repeatedly, almost as if it has become that character's <i>thing</i>, the one action we're supposed to associate with them. Granted, I think Mann is also doing that intentionally to suggest the repetitive, timeless nature of life at the Berghof, where nothing ever happens. <br /><br />The novel has 7 sections, which Mann arranges so that, by page 91 of 706 (going by my edition, the John E. Woods translation), you've arrived at the beginning of the 4th. A part of your brain can't help thinking that you've made some real progress, you're almost halfway there, just as Hans at this point in the story thinks he's already nearly halfway through his temporary stay, when in fact he and the reader both have a lot more time to spend on the mountain. And time does seem to distend, both Hans and the reader lose track of it- even the seasons on the mountain seem irregular, and only vaguely resemble the seasons in Hans's native Hamburg- as Hans settles into his daily routine and becomes acquainted with the variety of characters inhabiting the sanatorium. What I came to think of as pro-mountain and anti-mountain forces gather around Hans, which is not to say that most of them consider themselves such, or even discuss the mountain explicitly. Clavdia I'm afraid is in the pro-mountain camp, for example, simply because Hans wants to hook up with her, and therefore he's got one more reason to hang around. Behrens, the director and head doctor, rumored to be mildly tubercular himself (and also to have painted an intimate portrait of Clavdia, maybe not coincidentally), seems like a prisoner of the mountain who wants as much company up there as possible. Cousin Joachim, a soldier and resolutely anti-mountain, wants to get back to "the flatlands" as soon as possible to rejoin his men and carry out his duty, as he sees it. <br /><br />And then there's the humanist Settembrini and the proto-fascist Naptha, who begin intellectually jousting with each other somewhere around page 370. This is also right around the point in the novel where I overcame some initial ambivalence and really started to enjoy it, despite noticing that Mann still couldn't leave well enough alone- no sooner, for instance, did I have the thought, "why, it's almost as if these two pedagogues are engaged in mortal combat for Hans's very soul", then I swear that Mann had Hans think almost those very same words. These sections resemble more a philosophical dialogue than a traditional novel, and that can be disconcerting, but I felt myself slowly forgetting my preference for verisimilitude and starting to admire the novel for quietly transforming itself so many times, and encompassing so much- over 700 pages there are elements of bildungsroman, Lovecraftian hallucinations in the snow, philosophical dialogue, the vague suggestion of a ghost story, a postmodern impulse to describe the inner experience of the passage of time and boredom, as well as a lot that I probably didn't pick up on- while at the same time, "nothing" rigorously continues to happen, more or less. <br /><br />Besides, Mann really hit on something with the character of Naptha (Naptha even cites Everest at one point, approvingly, as evidence that there are still some things beyond the reach of human endeavor, knowledge, and Settembrini's beloved notion of progress- I would wager that Mann was probably reading in the paper about Mallory and Irvine's doomed expedition to Everest as he wrote, which assures me that my earlier reference to <i>Into Thin Air</i> at least wasn't entirely frivolous), who seems to foreshadow the dark decade of the 1930s. The Settembrini and Naptha scenes are compelling despite (or maybe because of) the fact that they're presented so that we understand we're supposed to see S. and N. as two sides of the same coin, both believing that the other's ideology will soon, inevitably, be swept aside by history. These scenes are even occasionally funny, with Mann describing the expressions of pedestrians in the small town where the characters are walking, the pedestrians befuddled at the spectacle of these two erudite windbags locked in mortal intellectual battle over the telos of the 20th century- even as we slowly zero in on the understanding that beneath all of Naptha's intellectual justifications lies the desire for murder. <br /><br />Despite Settembrini being a little naive about the inevitability of his vision of the future, I thought throughout the novel that he was actually giving Hans very good advice- one of the only characters to do so. To paraphrase in language that Thomas Mann probably wouldn't approve of- get the fuck out of here, Settembrini essentially tells him. What you're doing is wrong. It's wrong to hide from the world- wrong to let yourself become so enchanted by eros and thanatos that you no longer care about human affairs "down there", and the "real world" seems like an abstraction. You're <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[probably not even sick <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, for Christ's sake. You're abandoning your own time. Get away from this freaking mountain, and get back to living.<br /><br />But then again, what is it that Hans's cousin Joachim wants to get back to so badly? What can we read into the fact that Herr Naptha seems to be Joachim's number one fan? And what might Hans discover back in the flatlands? Is that really so preferable and so much saner than his purgatorial, increasingly ghostly existence at the Berghof? <br /><br />To talk about whether Hans ever takes Settembrini's advice would be a spoiler. Suffice to say that I enjoyed the last 200 pages or so a lot, and found them worth thinking about and discussing- except that it's probably better not to, in a review. I was very moved by the end of the novel, and felt that the experience had also been thought-provoking and meaningful, despite my occasional reservations. I especially liked <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[the way the enchantment was finally broken. Hans never comes to a conclusion sufficiently meaningful to get him off his bourgeois ass, never decides a thing- his decision is made for him by circumstance. Is that sort of the joke of this book, and maybe why it could be considered a parody of the bildungsroman? The fact that being exposed to all of these ideas never really get hims anywhere, and he's thrown into the bloody maw of history regardless? <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> It's recommended for reasonably adventurous readers with a little patience- probably not as a travel book, though. If I had tried to read this on a long bus or train ride, I think I would have been liable to throw it out a window, just as a character in Kesey's <i>Sometimes a Great Notion</i> does. It's really a book suited for reading at home, ideally for some weird, sedentary interregnum you might conceivably find yourself living through (no last names, please).<br /><br />In fact, considering that the characters theoretically can't go out into "the world" without risking their health and possibly their lives, you could also say that this is a book about the psychological and spiritual aspects of living in quarantine. I can just imagine an article in The Guardian a few months from now- as the pandemic hopefully continues to wind down- about these shadowy figures who simply refuse to re-enter society. I can imagine the comments- the schadenfreude, the moral censure, the outrage. Few will notice the parallels with a character from early-20th-century German literature. Parents weep as fully-vaccinated adult son insists pandemic, quote, "not over." We'll naturally have to invent some frightening name for these people, befitting their extreme danger to society. We'll wait and wonder if they'll ever return from the timeless inertia of the Covid era, just as the reader wonders if Hans will ever come down from that damn mountain.<br /> <br /><br /><br /><br />* (Note from December 2017) This is not a real review, just a reminder to myself that, before my flight to Russia a few months ago, I was told that my bag was overweight. I had to rifle through it in a panic, dripping sweat (I'm sometimes prone to anxiety), looking for heavy things to throw out, and one of the things I decided to throw out was this book, which is something like 700 pages and which I'd planned to bring to Russia with me. After all, I only now remember thinking, there are plenty of copies of <i>The Magic Mountain</i> in the world, and I can always get another. Alarmingly, however, I very quickly forgot not only that I'd thrown out the book in a garbage can at the Newark, New Jersey airport, not only that I'd ever owned it, but that a novel called the <i>The Magic Mountain</i> even existed. Until now, that is. Having remembered, due to a combination of unrelated circumstances that may never repeat themselves, I'd rather not forget again, since I do intend to read it, perhaps even in 2018, or, more realistically, 2019**.<br /><br />** (Make that March-April 2021)</span>
  <a data-text-id="14816418847614185942" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


