<div id="review_1603091302" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1603091302" />
    <a title="Yu" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/54680202-yu"><img alt="Yu" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1628151027p2/54680202.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1603091302?book_show_action=true">Apr 07, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Yu" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Yu" href="/user/show/54680202-yu">Yu</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/54680202-yu?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/54680202-yu?shelf=german-austrian">german-austrian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1603091302" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10907340418588326323"><b>The lure of death</b> Edited Sep 2019<br/><br/>One of my all time favorites. The magic mountain symbolizes a community detached from the flatland, the normal values, duties, history, time, indulging in its physical closeness to and spiritual longing for sickness and death. Hans Castorp, after entering into this fatigued, detached, and self-perpetuating community, became increasingly obsessed with the romanticism of sickness and death, which he considered noble. Mann not only associated sickness death with dec</span>
  <span id="freeText10907340418588326323" style="display:none"><b>The lure of death</b> Edited Sep 2019<br /><br />One of my all time favorites. The magic mountain symbolizes a community detached from the flatland, the normal values, duties, history, time, indulging in its physical closeness to and spiritual longing for sickness and death. Hans Castorp, after entering into this fatigued, detached, and self-perpetuating community, became increasingly obsessed with the romanticism of sickness and death, which he considered noble. Mann not only associated sickness death with decay, sensuality and love (<i>"all love is only disease transformed"</i>), but also with undisciplined pursuit of knowledge, a theme also explored in Death in Venice. <br /><br />The death of Hans' cousin Joachim Ziemssen (who symbolizes duty and asserts that opinions don't matter as long as one is a decent chap) in the incredibly touching chapter A Soldier, And Brave, marked a turning point for Hans' fascination with death, revealed to him the moral seriousness of death and the strength of piety and duty against death (<i>"For two things were unmistakable: first, that Joachim was approaching death in full consciousness, and second, that he consented to his state, and was in harmony with himself."</i>) In the chapter Snow, Hans made a choice between life and death, declaring that <i>"For the sake of goodness and love, man shall let death have no sovereignty over his thoughts. And with this—I awake."</i> Only what is life-worthy is love-worthy, and is honorable. The irony is that soon after he returned from the destructive snowstorm to the comfortable sanatorium, Hans forgot all about the thoughts he had in the snow. <br /><br />Hans Castorp finally returned to the flatland after 7 years of out-of-time sleep, to redeem respect for duty/tradition/mediocrity, and to eventually die in the Great War, perish in the universal feast of death with the same consciousness and harmony that Joachim had. There is a sense that this mediocre fate suits Hans Castorp well, whom Mann also characterizes as mediocre, <i>"though in an entirely honorable sense."</i><br /><br />The Magic Mountain is like a encyclopedia for the divisive forces on European continent before WWI (romanticism vs. rationalism, conservative vs. liberal, etc.) What I especially love about it is that those binary oppositions are not clear-cut, and other themes permeate them, enrich them, and eventually shatter them. Mann reveals to us that both sides are pedagogues, and the quarrels are nothing but a battle of noise. The novel ends with a question mark: <i>"Out of this universal feast of death, out of this extremity of fever, kindling the rain-washed evening sky to a fiery glow, may it be that love one day shall mount?"</i> A timeless masterpiece!</span>
  <a data-text-id="10907340418588326323" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
