    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_281904317" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/281904317" />
    <a title="Katia N" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7381993-katia-n"><img alt="Katia N" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1370960553p2/7381993.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/281904317?book_show_action=true">Feb 22, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Katia N" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Katia N" href="/user/show/7381993-katia-n">Katia N</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer281904317" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7253120562140634769">This book is a borderline somewhere between the physical reality and the reality of mind. It is by design a symbol and the object of time. The time it takes to read this novel is paced by the narrative itself. One cannot speed it up or slow it down. It possess its own life, its own time span and one needs to live it through if one is to read it. <br/><br/>I’ve tried to read it once before and got out of its hermetic world before properly getting in. I did not have Hans Castorp’s patience, fascination or p</span>
  <span id="freeText7253120562140634769" style="display:none">This book is a borderline somewhere between the physical reality and the reality of mind. It is by design a symbol and the object of time. The time it takes to read this novel is paced by the narrative itself. One cannot speed it up or slow it down. It possess its own life, its own time span and one needs to live it through if one is to read it. <br /><br />I’ve tried to read it once before and got out of its hermetic world before properly getting in. I did not have Hans Castorp’s patience, fascination or purpose. I got in this time and it is a tremendous structure. Mann wanted people to read the book twice if one is to get the most of it. And I might do it - I might read it again and then talk more about it.<br /><br />I would talk then about the depiction of death; its macabre side, but also its certain peacefulness Mann brings about.<br /><br />I would tell that Eros and Thanatos stop fighting with each other when they join in the service of Love and …. Care.<br /><br />I would talk about that this novel contains the accumulation of wisdom of the proceeding epochs as well as the idea of impossibility of this knowledge.<br /><br />I would talk about what kind of state of mind, collective and individual, makes a war possible if not inevitable. How the words stop become just that and become weapons. How those same words lose all the ability to mean anything at all. And only a wordless animal remains in the human being.<br /><br />I would ask wether a quest novel is possible if the main character spends the most of his time horizontally.<br /><br />I would talk about how a special sense of humour is the one of the main drivers of this book. <br /><br />But that would be after I read this novel once more. For now, Time:<br /><br /><i>Does Time, as it passes, really destroy?<br /> It may rip the fortress from its rock;<br /> but can this heart, that belongs to God,<br /> be torn from Him by circumstance?  <br /><br />Are we as fearfully fragile <br />as fate would have us believe? <br />Can we ever be severed <br />from childhood's deep promise?  <br /><br />Ah, the knowledge of impermanence<br /> that haunts our days <br />is their very fragrance.  <br /><br />We in our striving think <br />we should last forever, <br />but could we be used by the Divine<br /> if we were not ephemeral?</i><br /><br />R M Rilke</span>
  <a data-text-id="7253120562140634769" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


